formula.p:
Keep a four-ounce bottle of turpentine in your medicine case, also one of ipecac, which will have to be renewed every two months, as it spoils easily. The turpentine will be of use very frequently. As soon as your children, young or old, take a cold, saturate a flannel with turpentine and pin to the night dress, across the chest, so that when they sleep they will inhale it. Remember to pin on the outside of the dress, for if you bring it in contact with the bare skin it will be apt to burn the little ones. You may rub the chest with it by diluting it with camphorated oil, using say half of each; rub well over the chest, under the arms and across the back. You will also find this an excellent remedy 
when children complain of pains in their bowels;
 then heat the turpentine by setting the bottle in hot water, mix sweet oil with it, about equal parts, rub the stomach well with it and put hot flannels across the bowels, have them hot and dry; relief is sure to follow.
